abla ^{2}f(\mathbf {z}(t_{Q}))(\mathbf {y}-\mathbf {x})} for some t_{Q}\in (0,1)\,.

Let f:\mathcal {M}\mapsto \mathbb {R} be smooth on the Riemannian manifold \mathcal {M} . The Riemannian gradient \,\operatorname {grad}f(\boldsymbol {x})\, of f at \boldsymbol {x}\in \mathcal {M} is the unique tangent vector at \boldsymbol {x} such that
\mathrm {D}f(\boldsymbol {x})[\boldsymbol {v}]\ =\ \langle \operatorname {grad}f(\boldsymbol {x}),\boldsymbol {v}\rangle _{\boldsymbol {x}}\,,\quad \forall \,\boldsymbol {v}\in \mathrm {T}_{\boldsymbol {x}}\mathcal {M}. By extending the definition of f to the ambient Euclidean space \mathbb {R}^{n} , we can show that
\mathrm {grad} f(\mathbf {x}) = \mathcal {P}_{T_x \mathcal {M}}(\nabla f(\mathbf {x})) where {\mathcal {P}}_{\mathrm {T}_{\mathbf {x}}\mathcal {M}} is the orthogonal projector from \mathbb {R}^n to T_x \mathcal {M}

If f is first-order continuously differentiable, then f is convex iff
f(\boldsymbol {y}) \geq  f(\boldsymbol {x}) + \langle  \nabla  f(\boldsymbol {x}), \boldsymbol {y} - \boldsymbol {x}
\rangle

